[SPEAKER_01]: Indeed.

21:35.022 --> 21:38.507
[SPEAKER_01]: For your action on February the 19th, 1945, you won a bronze star.

21:38.707 --> 21:39.949
[SPEAKER_01]: Correct.

21:41.195 --> 21:50.884
[SPEAKER_01]: Let's go back to that day a little bit more and sort of what your job was and what you feel that you did, your entire unit did, that you earned the Bronze Star on that day.

21:52.973 --> 22:11.792
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, our job certainly was to get the guns in action as fast as we possibly could and help cover their advance on the pillboxes by putting fire into the apertures and keeping the enemy from returning fire as much as we could.

22:12.313 --> 22:17.378
[SPEAKER_00]: We're talking about numbers of pillboxes, we're not talking one, two, we're talking

22:17.358 --> 22:19.249
[SPEAKER_00]: Many.

22:19.652 --> 22:23.233
[SPEAKER_00]: So, as we did that,

22:23.467 --> 22:28.533
[SPEAKER_00]: We helped the infantry considerably by keeping the enemy's head down, so to speak.

22:29.153 --> 22:38.424
[SPEAKER_00]: But our guns were mounted, because of the sand, they were mounted on short little cargo vehicles called a Weasel.

22:39.305 --> 22:45.351
[SPEAKER_00]: And we made a frame, set the gun up on top of it, and they were in the LCVPs with us.

22:45.372 --> 22:49.136
