22:49.997 --> 22:51.178
[SPEAKER_00]: I see.

22:52.475 --> 23:12.238
[SPEAKER_00]: As we hit the beach and laid at that first parapet that shows up, I could see, well, there was just a great amount of mortar fire, artillery fire, and so it just seemed not logical to stay on the beach when my job was to get that gun that I could see up there, get it in action.

23:12.258 --> 23:20.288
[SPEAKER_00]: So my friend and I took off and we managed to get the gun in action very quickly and support the infantry.

23:20.622 --> 23:30.430
[SPEAKER_01]: I'd like, if I can, to read part of the citation that was given to you for thus the awarding of the Bronze Star Medal.

23:31.032 --> 23:35.745
[SPEAKER_01]: It says, despite heavy concentration of artillery, mortars, and machine gun fire,

23:36.147 --> 23:50.878
[SPEAKER_01]: which were falling around him, Private First Class Iyer, although fully exposed and unmindful of personal peril, ran back and forth between his ammunition supplies and the gun crew supplying the weapon at a time when its support was critically needed by the assaulting infantry.

23:50.898 --> 23:55.287
[SPEAKER_01]: When other members of the crew were wounded, he redoubled his efforts, serving

23:55.267 --> 24:00.276
[SPEAKER_01]: in the capacity of gunner in addition to maintaining the supply of ammunition.

24:00.296 --> 24:10.556
[SPEAKER_01]: As a result of his aggressive initiative, his gun remained in action despite casualties and provided material support to the infantry in establishing and maintaining the beachhead.

24:10.576 --> 24:14.423
[SPEAKER_01]: He gained his battle experience at Velo-Lavella and Bougainville,

24:14.403 --> 24:23.054
[SPEAKER_01]: Private first class hires outstanding actions and aggressive determination were in keeping with the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service.

24:23.375 --> 24:25.277
[SPEAKER_01]: Of course, this was T.E.

24:25.337 --> 24:27.380
[SPEAKER_01]: Bork signed this, Major General, U.S.

24:27.440 --> 24:29.963
[SPEAKER_01]: Marine Corps of the 5th Marine Division.

24:29.983 --> 24:31.505
[SPEAKER_01]: Obviously, it's a medal that you're very proud of.

24:31.666 --> 24:32.467
[SPEAKER_00]: Very proud.

24:32.487 --> 24:32.967
[SPEAKER_01]: Very proud.

24:33.288 --> 24:33.508
[SPEAKER_01]: You did.

24:33.758 --> 24:35.080
[SPEAKER_01]: And you also won the Purple Heart.

24:35.100 --> 24:39.665
[SPEAKER_01]: Of course, that Purple Heart was given because of your wounds.

24:39.685 --> 24:39.906
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

24:40.066 --> 24:41.327
[SPEAKER_01]: That's right.

24:41.888 --> 24:44.872
[SPEAKER_01]: You were wounded and you didn't really get to go back into action.

24:44.892 --> 24:48.096
[SPEAKER_01]: I think you said that they sent you to Guam to recover.

24:48.136 --> 24:50.639
[SPEAKER_01]: But by that time, the war was winding down.

24:50.699 --> 24:51.079
[SPEAKER_00]: Is that right?

24:51.099 --> 24:51.980
[SPEAKER_00]: Winding down, yes.

24:53.222 --> 24:56.966
[SPEAKER_00]: And so it was winding down.

24:56.986 --> 24:58.909
[SPEAKER_01]: Had you had your druthers, you would have liked to have gone back.

24:59.009 --> 25:00.711
[SPEAKER_00]: I wanted to go back, yes.

25:02.108 --> 25:03.811
[SPEAKER_01]: But you weren't able to.

25:03.851 --> 25:06.535
[SPEAKER_01]: It was winding down and you were still recovering.

25:06.555 --> 25:07.056
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

25:07.076 --> 25:08.298
[SPEAKER_01]: Indeed.

25:08.458 --> 25:10.521
[SPEAKER_01]: You came back to the United States.

25:11.082 --> 25:11.203
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

25:11.223 --> 25:16.231
[SPEAKER_01]: And talk about what you did after you got back to the United States and sort of the end of your service.

25:18.154 --> 25:22.701
[SPEAKER_00]: I was transferred to Great Lakes Naval Training Center.

25:23.001 --> 25:26.547
[SPEAKER_00]: It was in a casual company and we just did

25:26.830 --> 25:39.072
[SPEAKER_00]: I had jobs there because again, the war was winding down and the atomic bomb had been dropped and the European theater was quiet.

25:39.192 --> 25:44.622
[SPEAKER_00]: They had surrendered and then finally the Japanese surrendered and there was no more war to fight.

